#DESCRIPTION
#KEYWORDS('algebara', 'equations', 'domain')
#  Find the domain of a function root(a-bx)
#ENDDESCRIPTION

DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
		"extraAnswerEvaluators.pl");


$a = random(1,6,1);
$b = random(1,6,1);

TEXT(beginproblem());

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
Suppose that
\[ f(x) = (x+$a)(x-$b)^2.  \]
$BR
$BR
(A) Find all critical values of \(f\), compute their
average, and enter it below.
$BR
Note: If there are no critical values, enter -1000.
$BR
Average of critical values = \{ans_rule(12)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (num_cmp((2*$b - $a)/3) );

ANS( @answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
(B) Use interval notation to indicate where \( f(x) \) is increasing.
$PAR
$PAR
{\bf Note:} When using interval notation in WeBWorK, remember
that:
\begin{itemize}
\item You use 'I' for \(\infty\) and '-I' for \(-\infty\).
\item 'U' for the union symbol.
\item If you have extra boxes, fill each in with an 'x'.
\end{itemize}

Increasing:
$BR
\{ans_rule(25)\} 
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (interval_cmp("(-I,($b-2*$a)/3)U($b,I)"));  

ANS( @answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(C) Use interval notation to indicate where \( f(x) \) is decreasing.
$BR
Decreasing:
$BR
\{ans_rule(25)\}  
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (interval_cmp("(($b-2*$a)/3,$b)"));  

ANS( @answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(D) Find the \(x\)-coordinates of all local maxima of \(f\),
compute their average, and enter it below.
$BR
Note: If there are no local maxima, enter -1000.
$PAR
Average of \(x\) values = \{ans_rule(10)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (num_cmp(($b-2*$a)/3) );

ANS( @answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(E) Find the \(x\)-coordinates of all local minima of \(f\),
compute their average, and enter it below.
$BR
Note: If there are no local minima, enter -1000.
$PAR
Average of \(x\) values = \{ans_rule(10)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (num_cmp($b) );

ANS( @answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(F) Use interval notation to indicate where \( f(x) \) is concave up.
$BR
Concave up:
$BR
\{ans_rule(25)\}  
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (interval_cmp("((2*$b-$a)/3,I)"));  

ANS( @answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(G) Use interval notation to indicate where \( f(x) \) is concave down.
$BR
Concave down:
$BR
\{ans_rule(25)\}  
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (interval_cmp("(-I,(2*$b-$a)/3)"));  

ANS( @answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(H) Find all inflection points of \(f\), compute their
average, and enter it below.
$BR
Note: If there are no inflection points, enter -1000.
$BR
Average of inflection points = \{ans_rule(12)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (num_cmp((2*$b-$a)/3) );

ANS( @answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(I) Use all of the preceding information to sketch a
graph of \(f\).  When you're finished, enter a "1" in the box
below.
$BR
$BR
Graph Complete: \{ans_rule(12)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (num_cmp(1) );

ANS( @answers );

ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.
